Your account is eligible for a Deferred Payment Arrangement which is a payment option that extends large outstanding balances over time. With a Deferred Payment Arrangement an outstanding balance can be spread over 2 to 12 months.  Though finance charges will apply.  In order to create a Deferred Payment Arrangement, specific criteria must be met including the payment of any outstanding deposit balances and a required down payment.  The Deferred Payment Arrangement will take effect with the next billing cycle.  The total amount due displayed on the bill each month must be paid in full by the due date or the account will default off of the Deferred Payment Arrangement. To pay the entire balance of the Deferred Payment Arrangement prior to the end of the agreement term, please contact ComEd to speak to a Customer Service Representative.

If your electric usage varies widely from month to month or from season to season, Budget Billing allows you to spread your ComEd electric service costs evenly throughout the year. Here's how Budget Billing works: You pay a pre-arranged amount each month based on your energy use during the prior 12-month budget cycle. Your monthly Budget Bill payment will be adjusted every six months to keep the payment in line with your actual energy usage. Your budget plan will begin with your next bill. In order to go on the budget plan your account must be paid up to date. Continued participation requires that payments be made on or before the due date each month. You will automatically be removed from the Budget Billing program if you have two consecutive late payments or have three late payments within 12 months.

ComEd will credit your electric bill when you reduce your electricity use during Peak Time Savings Hours which typically occur for a few hours between 11 a.m. and 7 p.m. during the summer -- when most air conditioners are on, stores are open and factories are running. You will be notified on the day Peak Time Savings Hours occur - as early as 9 a.m. or at least 30 minutes prior to the start of each Peak Time Savings Hours. The amount your electric bill will be credited will be based on your current electricity usage and will appear as actual dollars off the total amount due on your next electric bill or the following bill. There is no penalty for not participating. You just won't earn a credit on your electric bill for that day. And, you can still participate in future Peak Time Savings Hours.

All workers and equipment are required to be a safe distance from the power lines until such time as  the lines have been effectively guarded against danger of incidental contact.  Once the energized lines have been protected, OSHA continues to require workers to maintain a ten foot clearance from the wires.
